{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_28","type":"command_execution","command":"/usr/bin/bash -lc \"rg -n \\\"2/6|33\\\\.33|dynamic-access|covered|uncovered|AnnotationCreator|coverage\\\" -S . ../3809-fe768431/human-intervention-logs/io.quarkus.gizmo:gizmo2:2.0.0.Beta10\"","aggregated_output":"./skills/README.md:22:It covers new-library metadata PRs, including titles like `[GenAI] Add support for com.fasterxml:classmate:1.5.1 using gpt-5.4`, and encodes the review rules already used in this repository: reject scaffold-only tests, keep test packages separate from library packages so tests do not bypass visibility boundaries, and question metadata coverage claims that are not supported by the diff.\n./skills/README.md:27:It covers compile-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the compile fix, preserve meaningful tests, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:32:It covers JVM runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the Java runtime fix, preserve meaningful tests and assertions, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:37:It covers native-image runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: verify the native path is fixed rather than skipped, keep metadata and test changes scoped, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-java-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR described as `fixes-java-run-fail` or one that fixes Java/JVM runtime test failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the Java runtime fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair tests, dependencies, or narrow runtime setup after an existing library version compiles, but the JVM-based test fails when it runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library already exists, so the goal is to restore Java runtime behavior for the new version while preserving meaningful test and dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:17:- Be more relaxed than `library-new-request`: do not reject only because a test resembles older coverage, stays in an existing package layout, or contains compatibility branches for multiple supported versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:18:- Do not accept changes that remove meaningful test coverage just to make `java` pass.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Native-image execution should remain enabled by default when the repaired test reaches the native lane. Do not accept changes that skip or short-circuit native-image behavior. When a test exercises behavior that fundamentally relies on open-ended dynamic class loading that native image cannot support, such as loading classes, JARs, generated bytecode, plugin implementations, or other class definitions that are only discovered after the native executable is built, accept the `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` catch pattern from `org.graalvm.internal.tck`. Reject raw native-only skips, bare `catch (Error)` blocks, and use of this pattern for ordinary reflection, resources, serialization, dynamic proxies, JNI, or missing reachability metadata.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:21:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:51:   - Compatibility branches are acceptable when they keep older and newer tested versions covered by the same test.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:56:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:60:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:61:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:71:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/runtime-surface change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:77:   - Prefer seeing the full target `test` lane green because a Java runtime fix can still reduce native-image coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:79:   - If CI is flaky but the diff and coverage comparison are sound, ask for a rerun instead of blocking on speculation.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:87:- Dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previous and new tested versions, or any apparent drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API/runtime surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:95:- Dynamic-access coverage drops without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:103:- The API or runtime behavior change is plausible but the PR does not explain why a coverage drop is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:110:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:112:- For deleted or bypassed coverage: say that the PR fixes Java runtime execution by removing coverage and should instead adapt the test to the new runtime behavior.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:114:- For native skips that does not depend on the open-ended dynamic class loading: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:163:        // Expected: Native Image cannot load plugin JARs discovered after build.\n./README.md:3:[![Libraries supported](https://img.shields.io/badge/dynamic/json.svg?label=libraries%20supported&query=%24.badges.librariesSupported&url=https%3A%2F%2Fraw.githubusercontent.com%2Foracle%2Fgraalvm-reachability-metadata%2Fstats%2Fcoverage%2Flatest%2Fbadges.json&style=flat-square&color=0A7EC2)](COVERAGE.md)\n./README.md:4:[![Tested library versions](https://img.shields.io/badge/dynamic/json.svg?label=tested%20library%20versions&query=%24.badges.testedLibraryVersions&url=https%3A%2F%2Fraw.githubusercontent.com%2Foracle%2Fgraalvm-reachability-metadata%2Fstats%2Fcoverage%2Flatest%2Fbadges.json&style=flat-square&color=BF8700)](COVERAGE.md)\n./README.md:5:[![Dynamic access coverage](https://img.shields.io/badge/dynamic/json.svg?label=dynamic%20access%20coverage&query=%24.badges.dynamicAccessCoverage&url=https%3A%2F%2Fraw.githubusercontent.com%2Foracle%2Fgraalvm-reachability-metadata%2Fstats%2Fcoverage%2Flatest%2Fbadges.json&style=flat-square&color=1F9D55)](COVERAGE.md)\n./README.md:6:[![Tested lines of code](https://img.shields.io/badge/dynamic/json.svg?label=tested%20lines%20of%20code&query=%24.badges.testedLinesOfCode&url=https%3A%2F%2Fraw.githubusercontent.com%2Foracle%2Fgraalvm-reachability-metadata%2Fstats%2Fcoverage%2Flatest%2Fbadges.json&style=flat-square&color=C2410C)](COVERAGE.md)\n./COVERAGE.md:3:![Coverage over time](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/oracle/graalvm-reachability-metadata/stats/coverage/latest/metrics-over-time.svg)\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:19:- Tests should execute under native image by default. Do not accept tests that disable themselves under native image. When a test exercises behavior that fundamentally relies on open-ended dynamic class loading that native image cannot support, such as loading classes, JARs, generated bytecode, plugin implementations, or other class definitions that are only discovered after the native executable is built, accept the `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` catch pattern from `org.graalvm.internal.tck`. Reject raw native-only skips, bare `catch (Error)` blocks, and use of this pattern for ordinary reflection, resources, serialization, dynamic proxies, JNI, or missing reachability metadata.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:21:- Require at least 50% reported dynamic-access coverage when there are dynamic-access calls to cover. Use the exploded stats files under `stats/<group>/<artifact>/<metadata-version>/stats.json` when available, and block the PR when dynamic-access coverage is below 50% or the PR provides no credible dynamic-access coverage evidence for non-zero dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:22:- Treat dynamic-access coverage counts as a minimum gate, not complete metadata evidence. They can miss metadata required through downstream libraries, so do not use high coverage alone to prove that the submitted metadata is complete or necessary.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:23:- Treat `0/0` dynamic-access coverage as a valid no-calls case, not as failed coverage. Do not reject a PR only because the exploded stats report `0/0` dynamic-access calls while the PR adds metadata; those stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:24:- Do not explicitly read or review individual metadata entries. Use the metadata entry count reported in the PR description for the metadata/dynamic-access mismatch check; do not manually count entries from metadata files. When the PR reports both library metadata entries and test-only metadata entries, use their sum as the PR-reported metadata entry count. Only request investigation when the covered dynamic-access call count is at least 75% higher than that PR-reported total.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:57:   - For metadata/dynamic-access mismatch checks, use only the metadata entry count reported in the PR description, such as `Metadata entries`, or legacy fields such as `Entries` and `Entries found` in older PRs; add `Test-only metadata entries` when the PR reports it; do not manually count metadata entries from files.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:61:5. Compare the PR claims, test, and reported coverage as one unit.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:62:   - If the PR claims specific coverage numbers that do not line up with the diff, ask for investigation.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:63:   - Confirm reported dynamic-access coverage is at least 50% when the stats include dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:64:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls and `reachability-metadata.json` is `{}`, that is acceptable as long as the test is library-specific and the scope is otherwise correct.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:65:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls while adding metadata, do not reject it on that basis alone; dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:66:   - If the stats report less than 50% coverage for non-zero dynamic-access calls, or no usable coverage signal for claimed dynamic-access behavior, ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:67:   - Ask for metadata/coverage mismatch investigation only when the covered dynamic-access call count is at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count, where the reported count is `Metadata entries` plus `Test-only metadata entries` when both are present. For older PRs, use legacy `Entries` or `Entries found` as the metadata entry count.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:90:  - Reported dynamic-access coverage is below 50% for non-zero dynamic-access calls, absent for claimed dynamic-access behavior, or not credible from the diff.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:97:- For native skips that does not depend on the open-ended dynamic class loading: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:101:- For insufficient dynamic-access coverage: say that new-library PRs need at least 50% dynamic-access coverage when there are dynamic-access calls to cover, and ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:102:- For unsupported coverage claims: ask for refreshed coverage evidence when the PR makes concrete coverage claims that are not supported by the diff.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:103:- For metadata/dynamic-access entry mismatch: ask for investigation only when covered dynamic-access calls are at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count, summing library and test-only metadata entries when both are reported. Do not manually count or argue from metadata contents.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:163:        // Expected: Native Image cannot load classes from JARs discovered after build.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-javac-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes Java compilation failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the compile fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair test sources or test dependencies after an existing library is bumped and the new version no longer compiles with the old test code. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library already exists, so the goal is to preserve working coverage across the version update rather than prove a brand-new metadata contribution from scratch.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:17:- Be more relaxed than `library-new-request`: do not reject only because a test resembles older coverage, stays in an existing package layout, or contains compatibility branches for multiple supported versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:18:- Do not accept changes that remove meaningful test coverage just to make `javac` pass.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Native-image execution should remain enabled by default when the repaired test reaches the native lane. Do not accept changes that skip or short-circuit native-image behavior. When a test exercises behavior that fundamentally relies on open-ended dynamic class loading that native image cannot support, such as loading classes, JARs, generated bytecode, plugin implementations, or other class definitions that are only discovered after the native executable is built, accept the `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` catch pattern from `org.graalvm.internal.tck`. Reject raw native-only skips, bare `catch (Error)` blocks, and use of this pattern for ordinary reflection, resources, serialization, dynamic proxies, JNI, or missing reachability metadata.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:20:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:21:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:50:   - Compatibility branches are acceptable when they keep older and newer tested versions covered by the same test.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:54:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:56:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:67:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:74:   - Prefer seeing the full target `test` lane green because a compile fix can still reduce runtime or native coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:76:   - If CI is flaky but the diff and coverage comparison are sound, ask for a rerun instead of blocking on speculation.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:84:- Dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previous and new tested versions, or any apparent drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:90:- The fix makes compilation pass by weakening or bypassing the test instead of adapting it to the changed API while preserving meaningful coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:92:- Dynamic-access coverage drops without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:100:- The API change is plausible but the PR does not explain why a coverage drop is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:107:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:109:- For deleted coverage: say that the PR fixes compilation by removing coverage and should instead adapt the test to the new API.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:110:- For native skips that does not depend on the open-ended dynamic class loading: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:121:- Bad compile repair that removes coverage:\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:154:        // Expected: Native Image cannot load generated classes discovered after build.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-native-image-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes a native-image runtime failure for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the runtime/native fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair metadata or tests after an existing library version compiles and builds a native image, but the native image fails when the test runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library is already supported, so the goal is to restore native-image behavior for a newer version while preserving existing dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:42:   - Accept narrow test edits that keep the same behavior covered across old and new versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:53:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:55:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:56:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - If metadata fixes make the native run pass but the dynamic-access ratio drops, ask for restored coverage first. Passing native execution is not enough by itself.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:67:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:76:   - If CI is flaky but the diff and coverage comparison are sound, ask for a rerun instead of blocking on speculation.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:84:- Dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previous and new tested versions, or any apparent drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:90:- The fix makes native execution pass by skipping the failing native path, disabling assertions, or removing coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:91:- Dynamic-access coverage drops without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:100:- The API or native runtime change is plausible but the PR does not explain why a coverage drop is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:107:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:109:- For native skips: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:22:| **Repository automation (Metadata Forge)** | Generate or repair metadata using LLM-driven pipelines. | Per coordinate, the toolkit can: (1) **add support for a new library** — generate a JUnit / Kotlin / Scala test suite, scaffold metadata, and iterate until JVM-mode tests pass and dynamic-access is collected ([`add_new_library_support.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/add_new_library_support.py)); (2) **fix a Java compilation (`javac`) failure** raised by a library version bump ([`fix_javac_fail.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_javac_fail.py)); (3) **fix a JVM-mode (`javaTest`) runtime failure** raised by a version bump ([`fix_java_run_fail.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_java_run_fail.py)); (4) **fix a `native-image` runtime failure** raised by a version bump ([`fix_ni_run.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_ni_run.py)); (5) **improve dynamic-access coverage** of already-supported libraries by targeting uncovered call sites; (6) **post-generation repair** of the metadata produced by a previous run ([`fix_post_generation_pi.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_post_generation_pi.py), [`fix_metadata_codex.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_metadata_codex.py)). Each task runs Gradle tasks against a worktree of this repo, appends a schema-validated metrics record, and — when invoked through [`forge/git_scripts/make_pr_*.py`](../forge/git_scripts/) — opens a PR for human review. See [forge/docs/architecture.md](../forge/docs/architecture.md). |\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:46:- A `stats/<groupId>/<artifactId>/<metadata-version>/stats.json` mirror of per-version metrics (dynamic-access call sites, coverage, lines of code, dependency information).\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:55:- Coverage collection (JaCoCo) and dynamic-access reporting per coordinate.\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:63:- Schedule-driven: full metadata sweep, new-library-version compatibility (every 4 hours), Docker image vulnerability scans, scheduled release every two weeks, scheduled coverage publication.\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:73:`publish-scheduled-coverage.yml` derives, from committed `stats/` and `metadata/**/index.json`:\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:74:- `latest/badges.json` — badges shown in the README (libraries supported, tested versions, dynamic-access coverage, tested LOC).\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:79:These are force-pushed to the `stats/coverage` branch.\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:84:1. **Add new library support** — generate a JUnit test suite, scaffold metadata, iterate until JVM-mode tests pass and dynamic-access metadata is collected.\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:87:4. **Improve coverage** of already-supported libraries by targeting uncovered dynamic-access call sites.\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:97:| `library-new-request` | Issue | Request to add support for a library that is not covered yet. |\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:98:| `library-update-request` | Issue / PR | Request or PR to improve support for an already-covered library, including coverage-improvement work. |\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:217:- **FR-T-7** Dynamic-access coverage between consecutive tested versions of a library must not regress (enforced by reviewer skills `review-fixes-javac-fail`, `review-fixes-native-image-run-fail`, `review-fixes-java-run-fail`).\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:256:- **NFR-7 Auditability.** Every Forge run produces a schema-validated metrics record; every coverage publish writes to a force-pushed branch with retained history.\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:271:- Mirrored stats under `stats/` and aggregated coverage artifacts on `stats/coverage`.\n./docs/CollectingMetadata.md:2:When the repository doesn’t have reachability metadata for a library you are using, the easiest way to generate it is to execute the test suite of the library with the Native Image Agent enabled. The agent is installed together with native-image and can be used to identify elements used during application execution that cannot be discovered by static analysis.\n./docs/CI.md:49:- [.github/workflows/publish-scheduled-coverage.yml](../.github/workflows/publish-scheduled-coverage.yml): scheduled/manual workflow that generates repository coverage badges and the coverage dashboard from exploded stats files under [stats/](../stats/) and repository [metadata/**/index.json](../metadata/), then force-pushes the published artifacts to the `stats/coverage` branch. The published branch only keeps `latest/badges.json`, `latest/metrics-over-time.svg`, and `history/history.json`.\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:77:- `--strategy-name NAME` select a predefined workflow strategy from `strategies/predefined_strategies.json`. Defaults to `javac_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.5`.\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:98:  [--keep-tests-without-dynamic-access] \\\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:123:- `--keep-tests-without-dynamic-access` keeps generated tests for dynamic-access workflows even if no dynamic-access call sites are covered.\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:259:- JaCoCo XML coverage parser:\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:383:coordinates, active dynamic-access classes, source-context paths, and Gradle\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:418:The `dynamic_access_iterative` workflow improves metadata accuracy by using the `generateDynamicAccessCoverageReport` Gradle task to identify which dynamic-access call sites (reflection, JNI, resources, serialization) are not yet covered by the generated tests. Instead of generating tests blindly, the workflow iterates class-by-class, sending the agent targeted prompts with the exact uncovered call sites for each class. After each attempt, the report is regenerated and coverage deltas are computed to decide whether to retry the same class or move on.\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:449:Composite strategies (run a primary workflow, then refine dynamic-access coverage):\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:453:| `javac_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4` | `pi` | `javac_iterative` |\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:456:#### Running a dynamic-access strategy\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:478:For the detailed function-level not